{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Panentheism has recently become a widely accepted and appreciated concept among scholars in the science-theology dialogue, and its theological repercussions have been discussed to great extent.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Yet, there remains to be studied in more detail the notion of the philosophical foundations of the term.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "A prominent gap in our understanding of these foundations is the potential similarity between the metaphysics of Hegel and Whitehead, their understanding of the transcendence and immanence of God, and their respective versions of panentheism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "In this article, I present a critical reflection on the possible resemblance between process thought and Hegelian metaphysics and philosophy of God.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "In the last section I refer to those who use panentheism within the science-theology dialogue.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "I try to specify which of the two versions of panentheism, that of Hegel or Whitehead, is more popular among those scholars.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Because of its reference to the God-world relationship, panentheism tends to be regarded a purely theological concept.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "But it is not.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Its origins are in philosophy and go back to Plato and Neoplatonism.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Transmitted by Pseudo-Dionysius, John Scotus Eriugena and Nicholas of Cusa, panentheism found new expression in German Idealism.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "It was within this philosophical tradition that the very term 'panentheism' (Allingottlehre) was coined (K.C.F. Krause) and the metaphysical shift from substance to subject found its culmination (G.W. Hegel).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "God expressing or unfolding himself in the world is understood as the Creator who remains in a dynamic reciprocity with creation.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "This expressivist version of philosophical panentheism became a source of theological panentheistic propositions presented in the contemporary science/theology debate.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "But there is one more crucial point of reference for many of those who adopt philosophical panentheism, namely Whitehead's philosophy of process.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Built within the Whitehedian process framework, Charles Hartshorne's concept of a dipolar God influenced not only John Cobb and David Griffin who applied it to postmodern theology and social justice issues.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "It turned out to be inspiring also for those trying to bridge science and religion.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Barbour, Clayton and Ward make a clear reference to the philosophy of process.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Although Peacocke distances himself from this tradition, his concept of transcendence-in-immanence and his understanding of the God-world relation resemble the theology proposed by Hartshorne as well.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "After we have named two main philosophical sources of contemporary panentheism, the question should be asked whether they are complementary or distinctive.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "Does the Whitehedian dipolar notion of God resemble expressivist Hegelian Panentheism?",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "Is there a relation between these two synoptic thinkers in the tradition of western philosophy?",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "The case is problematic.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "There are thinkers, who - following Robert Ellis - claim, that we should not treat Whitehead as 'a sort of Melchizedek of twentieth-century philosophy - arriving on the scene to bless Abrahams and slay other warriors without ancestry and obvious philosophical lineage.'",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "For them Whithehead's dependence on German and British Idealism is undeniable.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "On the other hand, however, there are scholars who tend to support the opposite position expressed by Victor Lowe who says: 'Only in his metaphysics - particularly in his doctrine of coherence - is a Hegelian influence notable.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "Had there never been a Hegel, (…) Whitehead would still have been led to that [doctrine] by his instinctive acknowledgement that the truth is complex, and that different thinkers have got hold of contrasting aspects of it.'",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU27": {
      "text": "This position appears to be in agreement with Whitehead himself, who said at one point: 'I have never been able to read Hegel: I initiated my attempt by studying some remarks of his on mathematics which struck me as complete nonsense.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU28": {
      "text": "It was foolish of me, but I am not writing to explain my good sense.'",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU29": {
      "text": "As one can see, different scholars seem to support opposite positions, which shows the need for clarifying the problem.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
